"{\n    \"introduction\": \"The election of Andrew Jackson in 1828 marked a pivotal shift towards a more inclusive democracy, triggering the 'era of the common man'. It heralded a new political era with greater participation by the ordinary people. Leading up to the election, Jackson capitalized on his military reputation and the expanding suffrage that included more white male voters, while his supporters crafted his image as a man of the people, contrasting with the perceived elitism of his opponents.\",\n    \"name\": \"Jackson's Election\",\n    \"description\": \"Andrew Jackson's election as President sparked a democratic expansion and the rise of the Democratic Party, influencing American politics deeply.\",\n    \"dates\": [\"1828\", \"1829\"],\n    \"effects\": [\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Petticoat affair\",\n        \"score\": 3\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Indian Removal Act\",\n        \"score\": 8\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Nullification Crisis\",\n        \"score\": 7\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Bank War\",\n        \"score\": 9\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Founding of the Whig Party\",\n        \"score\": 5\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Panic of 1837\",\n        \"score\": 4\n      },\n      {\n        \"name\": \"Specie Circular\",\n        \"score\": 3\n      }\n    ],\n    \"conclusion\": \"The election of Andrew Jackson signaled the emergence of a more democratic political system and a shift in power towards a broader electorate. His presidency saw significant events that shaped the nation's future, including policies towards Native Americans, the economy, and the two-party system.\",\n    \"people\": [\n      \"Andrew Jackson\",\n      \"John Quincy Adams\",\n      \"Henry Clay\",\n      \"Martin Van Buren\"\n    ],\n    \"places\": [\n      \"United States\",\n      \"Washington, D.C.\",\n      \"Tennessee\",\n      \"The American Frontier\"\n    ],\n    \"themes\": [\n      \"Democracy